hom.sense:
hab-a, aor. yahib-u (Ṣ, Ḳ) and yahub-u, (Ḳ,) the latter dev. from rule, and not found in other lexicons, but see what is cited above from Lb, that hb- is one of the twenty-eight verbs which thus deviate from rule, (TA,) inf. n. habiybN and hibaAbN and hib-apN; 
and Ahtb-↓; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) 
and habohaba↓, (Ḳ,) inf. n. habohabapN; (TA;) ‡ He (a goat) was excited with lust: (TA;) or uttered a sound, or cry, [or rattled,] and was excited by desire of the female; or uttered a sound, or cry, [or rattled,] when so excited, or at rutting-time: (Ṣ, Ḳ:) or habohaba signifies he uttered a sound, or cry, [or rattled,] at rutting-time: (TA:) or hab-a, 
inf. n. hibaAbN and habiybN; 
and Ahtb-↓; He (a stallion-camel, &c.) desired copulation. (M.)

entry.sense:
habata, 
aor. _i {yahobitu} 
see habiytN.

habyTN 
‡ Lean, or emaciated, by reason of disease; 
as also mahobuwTN↓: (Ḳ:) both are applied to a camel, signifying whose fatness has become diminished; 
as also haAbiTN↓: (TA:) and the first, to a she-camel, signifying lean, and lank in the belly; (AO, Ṣ;) or to a wild bull, to which a she-camel is likened in respect of her swiftness, and her briskness, liveliness, or sprightliness (IB:) 
and ↓the second signifies rendered lean. or emaciated, by disease, so that his flesh quivers. (TA.)

hom.sense:
Ahjr fiI manoTiqihi, (Ṣ,* Mgh, Mṣb, Ḳ,) or simply Ahjr, (A,) inf. n. UihojaArN (Ṣ, Ḳ) and hujorN, (Lḥ, Kr, Ḳ,) or the latter is, correctly speaking, a simple subst., (TA,) He spoke, or uttered, foul, evil, bad, abominable, or unseemly, language: (Ṣ, A, Mgh, Ḳ:) or he did so much; beyond what he used to do before; 
as also hajara↓, 
aor. _u {yahojuru}, (Mṣb,) inf. n. hajorN: (L, TA:) and in like manner, he talked much of that which was not fit, suitable, meet, or proper. (Ṣ.)

